vulnerabilities.description: Airtable Base ID exposed: appleLoginButtonOn
vulnerabilities.recommendation: Review Base ID usage and implement proper access controls
vulnerabilities.background: Airtable bases are identified by Base IDs which are used in API calls and internal routing. Exposing Base IDs can facilitate reconnaissance and unauthorized API usage when combined with leaked credentials.
vulnerabilities.impact: An attacker who obtains valid Base IDs can more easily target specific bases, attempt credential stuffing against corresponding APIs, or correlate other leaked information to pivot into data exfiltration attacks.

vulnerabilities.background: Airtable bases are identified by Base IDs which are used in API calls and internal routing. Exposing Base IDs can facilitate reconnaissance and unauthorized API usage when combined with leaked credentials.
vulnerabilities.impact: An attacker who obtains valid Base IDs can more easily target specific bases, attempt credential stuffing against corresponding APIs, or correlate other leaked information to pivot into data exfiltration attacks.

vulnerabilities.background: Airtable bases are identified by Base IDs which are used in API calls and internal routing. Exposing Base IDs can facilitate reconnaissance and unauthorized API usage when combined with leaked credentials.

vulnerabilities.impact: An attacker who obtains valid Base IDs can more easily target specific bases, attempt credential stuffing against corresponding APIs, or correlate other leaked information to pivot into data exfiltration attacks.

vulnerabilities.description: Cookie lacks the 'HttpOnly' attribute
vulnerabilities.recommendation: Set the 'HttpOnly' attribute for all sensitive cookies to prevent client-side script access.
vulnerabilities.background: The 'HttpOnly' attribute prevents client-side scripts (like JavaScript) from accessing the cookie, which is a critical defense against session theft via Cross-Site Scripting (XSS).
vulnerabilities.impact: If an XSS vulnerability exists, an attacker can steal the session cookie and hijack the user's session if the 'HttpOnly' attribute is missing.

vulnerabilities.description: Content Security Policy contains 'unsafe-inline' directive, allowing arbitrary style execution
vulnerabilities.evidence: {'type': 'exact', 'pattern': "Content-Security-Policy: style-src 'unsafe-inline' https:; block-all-mixed-content; object-src 'none'; base-uri 'none'; report-uri https://airtable.com/.csp/report; script-src 'nonce-Qstp9bUORBiA' 'unsafe-inline' 'strict-dyna"}
vulnerabilities.recommendation: Remove 'unsafe-inline' from CSP directives. Use nonces or hashes instead.
vulnerabilities.background: Using 'unsafe-inline' in CSP allows the execution of inline scripts or styles, which significantly weakens the security provided by CSP. Specifically, 'unsafe-inline' in style-src can allow an attacker to perform style-based data exfiltration.
vulnerabilities.impact: An attacker can bypass CSP protections to execute malicious scripts (if in script-src) or manipulate page styles to exfiltrate sensitive data or perform UI redressing.

vulnerabilities.description: CSP lacks 'form-action' directive, allowing potential form hijacking
vulnerabilities.evidence: {'type': 'exact', 'pattern': "Content-Security-Policy: style-src 'unsafe-inline' https:; block-all-mixed-content; object-src 'none'; base-uri 'none'; report-uri https://airtable.com/.csp/report; script-src 'nonce-Qstp9bUORBiA' 'unsafe-inline' 'strict-dyna"}
vulnerabilities.recommendation: Add a 'form-action' directive to your CSP to restrict where forms can be submitted.
vulnerabilities.background: The 'form-action' directive restricts the URLs which can be used as the target of a form submission from a given context. Without this directive, forms can be hijacked via HTML injection to send sensitive data to an attacker's server.
vulnerabilities.impact: An attacker with HTML injection capabilities could hijack forms on the page to steal user credentials or other sensitive information submitted via forms.

vulnerabilities.description: AJAX requests may lack security headers
vulnerabilities.background: AJAX requests without proper security headers like X-Requested-With can be vulnerable to CSRF attacks. These headers help servers distinguish between legitimate AJAX requests and malicious cross-site requests.
vulnerabilities.impact: Missing AJAX security headers increases the risk of CSRF attacks, where malicious websites can make unauthorized AJAX requests on behalf of authenticated users, potentially leading to data theft or unauthorized actions.

vulnerabilities.description: No Permissions-Policy header found
vulnerabilities.recommendation: Implement a Permissions-Policy to control which browser features are available.
vulnerabilities.background: Permissions-Policy (formerly Feature-Policy) allows web developers to selectively enable, disable, and modify the behavior of certain APIs and web features in the browser.
vulnerabilities.impact: Absence of Permissions-Policy allows all supported features to be used, increasing the attack surface if the site is compromised or if it embeds untrusted third-party content.
